Reference-contexts: Similarly, QoS guarantees can be provided with admission control and resource reservation. However, such approaches are not possible in the current Internet environment, and are still far from being supported in commercial operating systems. We propose a novel toolkit-based software feedback <ref> [1, 2, 3] </ref> approach to client/server synchronization, dynamic QoS control and system adaptiveness in the Internet environment. We have constructed a distributed real-time MPEG video and audio player [1], and used it as a test-bed to study the effectiveness of software feedback mechanisms, and to investigate the toolkit approach. <p> We propose a novel toolkit-based software feedback [1, 2, 3] approach to client/server synchronization, dynamic QoS control and system adaptiveness in the Internet environment. We have constructed a distributed real-time MPEG video and audio player <ref> [1] </ref>, and used it as a test-bed to study the effectiveness of software feedback mechanisms, and to investigate the toolkit approach. THE DISTRIBUTED VIDEO AUDIO PLAYER with a video server, an audio server and a client distributed across the Internet. <p> The QoS metrics used to measure the actual QoS level of the player include video display frame rate, defined in terms of frames-per-second (fps), and smoothness <ref> [1] </ref>, defined as a measurement of the deviation of the playback in question from a perfect play. A perfect play is defined as a play in which no frames are dropped, and all frames are displayed at the correct time. <p> A perfect play is defined as a play in which no frames are dropped, and all frames are displayed at the correct time. The user can specify a desired frame rate, and the player tries to yield a display frame rate up to the user-specified frame rate. The player <ref> [1] </ref> makes extensive use of software feedback [2, 3], a technique similar to hardware feedback mechanisms such as phase-lock loops.
